lemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud De Bigod was born in 1099. She had at least 1 son with Ailwardus de Wymondham. She died in 1196, at the age of 97."},"et":{"1099–1196":"1099–1196","1087–Male":"1087–Surnud","1131–1211":"1131–1211","1117–Male":"1117–Surnud","1119–Male":"1119–Surnud","1121–Male":"1121–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1117":"1117","ABT 1121":"umbes 1121","1211":"1211","1099":"1099","1121":"1121","1131":"1131","1087":"1087","1196":"1196","ABT 1117":"umbes 1117","1150":"1150","ABT 1119":"umbes 1119","1119":"1119","England":"England",",,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1099–1196":"1099–1196","1087–Male":"1087–Kuollut","1131–1211":"1131–1211","1117–Male":"1117–Kuollut","1119–Male":"1119–Kuollut","1121–Male":"1121–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1117":"1117","ABT 1121":"noin 1121","1211":"1211","1099":"1099","1121":"1121","1131":"1131","1087":"1087","1196":"1196","ABT 1117":"noin 1117","1150":"1150","ABT 1119":"noin 1119","1119":"1119","England":"England",",,England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1099–1196":"1099–1196","1087–Male":"1087–Décédé","1131–1211":"1131–1211","11